[Indeed laboratory data would be helpful to determine if this was a
toxicosis or an infectious disease. There are clearly a number of
different issues that could/should be ruled out if more data were
available.

We are informed that samples from the dairy buffaloes in Landhi's
Cattle Colony are being collected and processed for Haemorhagic
Septicaemia (caused by _Pasteurella multocida_) and rinderpest
tests, as well as for investigations for poison/toxin in the feed
(the most probable cause of mortality). The sampling and testing are
collaboratively undertaken by the National Veterinary Laboratory, the
National Agricultural Research Centre and FAO experts, co-located in
Islamabad. Results are anticipated with interest.

Landhi cattle colony consists of approximately 2000 farms with a
total population of approximately 300 000 animals, of which 90
percent are Asian buffalos and furthermore a high number of free
ranging sheep and goats.

Unfortunately there seem to be no
internationally-obligatory mechanism requiring the notification of
mass-intoxications in food animals. Such a mechanism (to
involve national food-safety authorities?) would be instrumental in
preventing the exposure of consumers, within the affected country as
well as in external markets, to food-related hazards and will enhance
the withdrawal or retention of the relevant products if/when
prescribed. A recent example is the mass mortality in camels in Saudi
Arabia, suspected (unofficially) to be caused by the feed-additive
ionophore Salinomycin (see references). This event, allegedly
involving more than 5000 camels, has not been officially notified by
the Saudi authorities though camels are exported to other countries
and camel meat is widely consumed in the Middle East. No final
laboratory results, repeatedly requested by ProMED-mail, have become
available so far. - Mods.TG/AS]
